  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Protected and safe access to education as an emergency response for vulnerable communities in the West Bank.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Children in the West Bank, including East Jerusalem, face severe and chronic protection challenges getting to and from school every day. They cross Israeli military check points and go through closed military zones where they can experience harassment and even violence. On their daily commute, they pass by Israeli settlements which can also be a source of abuse, harassment and violence.

The project will contribute to the 2018 HRP Education objective of improving safe access to quality learning environment in vulnerable areas by providing protective presence and accompaniment to 6,700 students and 200 teaches in H2, South Hebron Hills and other selected locations in Area C and East Jerusalem. Children and teachers facing obstacles to schools or children exposed to risks of harassment on their way to schools will be accompanied by international volunteers. 

This intervention has been developed in consultation with the affected communities who express increased demand for it. Several assessments of the intervention have shown that parents are likely to send their children to school when there is protective presence and that students, and teachers feel safer when accompanied on their way to and from school.

UNICEF will use an evidence-based study to evaluate the current protective presence approach and its effectiveness and suggest alternative modalities that would mitigate the risks of relying on the international NGO partner in case of access constraints. UNICEF team is also responsible for monitoring of the implementation to ensure quality and course-correct if needed and achievement of all planned objectives.</narrative>
  </description>
